xplain how and when the poor secured access to these makeshifts and suggest how the balance of these strategies might change over time or be modified by gender, life-cycle and geography. This book represents the single most significant attempt in print to supply the English 'economy of makeshifts' with a solid, empirical basis and to advance the concept of makeshifts from a vague but convenient label to a more precise yet inclusive definition.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCharityxHistory. 0aIncomezEnglandxHistory. 0aPoorzEnglandxHistoryy18th century. 0aPoorzEnglandxHistoryy19th century. 0aPublic welfarezEnglandxHistory. 0aSocial networkszEnglandxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aCowpe.  aEnglish poverty.  aLancashire rural communities.  abread.  acash flow exigencies.  acredit.  adebt.  adole.  afuel.  agender.  ageography.  alife-cycle.  amakeshift economy.  apamphlet literature.  apawnbroking.  apoor law.  arural agricultural poor.  asocial crime.  asurvival strategies.  avoluntary charity.1 aBarrett, Sam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHanly, Margaret, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHindle, Steve, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKing, Steve, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKing, Steven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLloyd, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShore, Heather, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTomkins, Alannah, econtributor.4ct